WEBVTT

00:00:02.960 --> 00:00:04.760
NARRATOR: Humans...

00:00:04.760 --> 00:00:08.230
Without a doubt, the
smartest animal on earth.

00:00:08.230 --> 00:00:13.860
Yet we're unmistakably
tied to our ape origins.

00:00:13.860 --> 00:00:15.260
Millions of years ago,

00:00:15.260 --> 00:00:19.160
we were apes, living
ape lives in Africa.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:21.700
So how did we get from that...

00:00:21.700 --> 00:00:24.800
to this?

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:26.460
What happened?

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:30.230
What set us on the
path to humanity?

00:00:30.230 --> 00:00:32.160
The questions are huge.

00:00:32.160 --> 00:00:35.300
But at last,
there are answers.

00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:39.430
More than six million years
ago we took that first step

00:00:39.430 --> 00:00:41.860
to separate from the apes.

00:00:41.860 --> 00:00:43.960
DON JOHANSON: We see the
launching of the career

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:46.500
that ultimately led
to Homo sapiens.

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:51.500
NARRATOR: And three
million years ago, we see
the roots of our big brain

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.530
begin to take hold
in a tiny creature

00:00:54.530 --> 00:00:57.600
more like a chimp than a human.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:00:59.460
PETER deMENOCAL: The
frontier of human evolution

00:00:59.460 --> 00:01:04.500
is really being brought
to this razor sharp edge.

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:07.000
NARRATOR: And we now know
that for millions of years,

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.100
many different humanlike
species lived together

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:15.360
on the planet until one
day there was only us,

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:16.900
Homo sapiens,

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:21.330
the most complex,
adaptable animal on earth.

00:01:21.330 --> 00:01:25.160
So how did we get
this way, and why?

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:30.360
A radical new theory reveals how
episodes of cataclysmic change

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:33.900
forced our ancestors
to adapt or die.

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:37.230
MARK MASLIN: I think
we should actually look
to our proud ancestry

00:01:37.230 --> 00:01:38.760
and how we evolved in
East Africa and say,

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.500
That's how we survived that.

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:42.030
We can survive the future.

00:01:42.030 --> 00:01:45.060
NARRATOR: So get ready for a
ride through millions of years

00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:46.560
of our history.

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:49.930
Its the story of becoming
human-- our story--

00:01:49.930 --> 00:02:06.830
right now, on NOVA.

00:02:06.830 --> 00:02:10.460
